[takes deep breath]

03:28.817 --> 03:30.819
[quiet chatter]

03:32.690 --> 03:34.779
♪

03:34.823 --> 03:36.520
[sighs]

03:44.659 --> 03:47.836
VIVIAN:
The point of proctorship is
to ensure

03:47.879 --> 03:49.446
a surgeon's skills
have not diminished

03:49.490 --> 03:51.013
during a leave of absence.

03:51.056 --> 03:53.058
The guidelines are rigorous.

03:54.973 --> 03:57.585
But then again,
so is heart surgery.

03:59.630 --> 04:02.894
"A proctorship's
successful conclusion is a win

04:02.938 --> 04:06.202
for the returning surgeon
and the patients in his care."

04:06.246 --> 04:07.856
It's all there.Well, I want to start out

04:07.899 --> 04:09.205
on the right foot,
and I want to make sure

04:09.249 --> 04:11.990
that the terms are clear
and easy to follow.

04:12.034 --> 04:15.951
I just don't know that
clarity is the issue, Sam.

04:15.994 --> 04:17.953
I mean, we're talking about
your father.

04:17.996 --> 04:20.172
We're talking about
my colleague.

04:20.216 --> 04:22.958
I am in as a doctor.
Out as a daughter, remember?

04:23.001 --> 04:25.003
Good. So you've drawn
your boundaries with your...

04:25.047 --> 04:27.832
colleague, but, um...

04:27.876 --> 04:29.312
What about Lex?

04:29.356 --> 04:31.880
Hmm? Have you, uh,
have you talked to her?

04:31.923 --> 04:34.491
Uh... [scoffs] About work, yes.

04:34.535 --> 04:37.929
About having an affair
with my father, no, not so much.

04:37.973 --> 04:39.366
But she's your best friend.

04:39.409 --> 04:40.932
I appreciate your concern.

04:40.976 --> 04:43.283
But right now,
this department head

04:43.326 --> 04:46.111
needs her CMO more than
your daughter needs her mother.

04:46.155 --> 04:49.550
I'm gonna get these guidelines
to Dr. Griffith right away.

04:49.593 --> 04:50.855
Thank you.

04:52.857 --> 04:55.164
Hey, um,
sorry to interrupt.

04:55.207 --> 04:57.558
Uh, year-end projections
just came in.

04:57.601 --> 04:58.776
Thank you, Malcolm.

04:58.820 --> 05:00.430
I'd like to review those
before tomorrow.

05:02.650 --> 05:04.304
Hi.

05:04.347 --> 05:06.436
Hi. [clears throat]

05:06.480 --> 05:10.005
I'll be, uh, in my office.

05:11.876 --> 05:14.096
So, what's tomorrow?

05:14.139 --> 05:15.793
[chuckles] Board meeting.

05:15.837 --> 05:17.012
Does that mean you're preparing

05:17.055 --> 05:18.840
for Mr. Byron Kingsley's
arrival?

05:18.883 --> 05:21.625
He is the chairman of the board.So, tomorrow

05:21.669 --> 05:24.759
is Take Your Dad to Work day
for both of us?[laughs]

05:24.802 --> 05:26.717
[chuckles]
Uh, yeah.

05:26.761 --> 05:29.807
Yeah, always puts me a little
on edge when he comes in.

05:29.851 --> 05:31.809
Is there anything I can do
to help?

05:31.853 --> 05:34.638
You could go to dinner with me
tonight.

05:34.682 --> 05:36.640
♪

05:36.684 --> 05:37.989
Well...

05:38.033 --> 05:41.036
Dinner for me, uh,
is usually takeout

05:41.079 --> 05:44.126
in the lab,
awaiting test results.

05:44.169 --> 05:45.954
And for me it's takeout
on the couch,

05:45.997 --> 05:47.303
watching Cupcake Wars.

05:47.347 --> 05:49.784
You bake?I watch other people bake.

05:49.827 --> 05:52.352
We should go out to dinner.

05:57.792 --> 05:58.923
JOEY:Wow.

05:58.967 --> 06:00.490
Nice haircut, Donna.

06:00.534 --> 06:02.405
Thank you.
Morning, doctors.

06:02.449 --> 06:03.667
What do you say, Donna?

06:03.711 --> 06:05.365
Is today the day
we run away together?

06:05.408 --> 06:07.845
Try again next week
when my wife's out of town.

06:07.889 --> 06:09.934
ISAN:No one else thinks
this is weird?

06:09.978 --> 06:11.980
Griff was our boss,
and now he's, what,

06:12.023 --> 06:14.025
a resident like us?He's being supervised.

06:14.069 --> 06:15.723
It's how proctorship works.

06:15.766 --> 06:18.203
Lex, you agree,
it's weird, right?

06:18.247 --> 06:20.728
It's only weird
if you make it weird.

06:20.771 --> 06:21.859
How do I make it weird?

06:21.903 --> 06:23.861
You try too hard with him, Isan,

06:23.905 --> 06:25.123
and it always backfires.

06:25.167 --> 06:26.386
You end up tripping
over your shoelaces,

06:26.429 --> 06:27.561
dropping your instruments.

06:27.604 --> 06:29.389
[scoffs]Cornering him in the men's room.

06:29.432 --> 06:32.348
I don't corner him
in the men's room, Joey.

06:32.392 --> 06:34.611
No, you just told him a
knock-knock joke at the urinal.

06:34.655 --> 06:36.178
I was making
small talk.

06:36.221 --> 06:38.659
It's not my fault we're forced
to pee next to each other.

06:38.702 --> 06:40.617
Women get
their own private stalls.[elevator bell dings]

06:40.661 --> 06:43.272
Oh, right. This is all because
the world is unfair to men.

06:43.315 --> 06:45.535
Morning, everyone.ALL: Morning.

06:45.579 --> 06:47.972
Good morning.Thank you. Let's see.

06:48.016 --> 06:50.540
Eval for a mitral
valve replacement.

06:50.584 --> 06:53.021
Atrial fib.
Morning.

06:54.196 --> 06:55.502
Right on time.

06:55.545 --> 06:57.242
Consider that
an accomplishment, do you?

06:57.286 --> 06:59.549
Well, given how far away
my new parking spot is,

06:59.593 --> 07:00.811
and then I have to...What do we have?

07:00.855 --> 07:02.944
Patient with a lung mass
needs VATS for biopsy.

07:02.987 --> 07:04.424
And what else?

07:04.467 --> 07:06.338
Ten-month-old with a persistent
cough and a new murmur.

07:06.382 --> 07:08.036
Peds is asking for a consult.

07:08.079 --> 07:09.472
Uh, since when do we take
pediatric cases?

07:09.516 --> 07:11.909
Oh, since I instituted
a cross-departmental policy

07:11.953 --> 07:13.389
to integrate care,

07:13.433 --> 07:16.087
which has significantly
improved patient satisfaction.

07:16.131 --> 07:17.872
What's next,
a tonsillectomy?

07:17.915 --> 07:19.395
We are gonna start
with the peds case.

07:19.439 --> 07:21.005
And Dr. Griffith will join us

07:21.049 --> 07:23.007
after he pages Dr. Chen
in radiology.

07:23.051 --> 07:25.009
And why am I paging Dr. Chen?

07:25.053 --> 07:27.098
Well, I have a feeling he's
looking for his white coat.

07:27.142 --> 07:29.274
Before you offer opinions

07:29.318 --> 07:30.667
on the cases I take,

07:30.711 --> 07:32.408
please make sure you've
dressed yourself properly,

07:32.452 --> 07:34.410
Doctor.

07:35.498 --> 07:37.718
♪

07:44.855 --> 07:46.248
[baby coughs]

07:46.291 --> 07:47.771
[fussing]

07:47.815 --> 07:49.207
First, they said
it was a cold,

07:49.251 --> 07:50.513
and then they sent us here.

07:50.557 --> 07:52.123
Nobody can tell us what's wrong.

07:52.167 --> 07:53.342
And his cough keeps
getting worse.

07:53.385 --> 07:54.517
When did it start?

07:54.561 --> 07:56.693
Weeks ago.
What, two, three?

07:56.737 --> 07:59.391
Ellie, for the last time,
put on your shoes.

07:59.435 --> 08:01.132
How Bohemian.

08:01.176 --> 08:03.134
Is there any family history
of heart problems?

08:03.178 --> 08:04.745
Not that I know of.[baby cries]

08:04.788 --> 08:05.789
Let's get a nebulizer

08:05.833 --> 08:07.008
with 2.5 milligrams[coughs]

08:07.051 --> 08:08.792
of albuterol.You got it.

08:08.836 --> 08:11.491
His heart muscle does appear
to be inflamed,

08:11.534 --> 08:13.318
so I'd like to put him
on an anti-inflammatory

08:13.362 --> 08:14.363
and do a breathing treatment

08:14.406 --> 08:15.930
to calm the cough.

08:15.973 --> 08:17.540
He's just been suffering
so much.

08:17.584 --> 08:20.064
Let's also run
a 12-lead EKG

08:20.108 --> 08:21.457
and do a bacterial culture.

08:21.501 --> 08:23.241
Well, it's most likely viral,
so..,

08:23.285 --> 08:24.939
Well, given the abnormality
in the X-ray,

08:24.982 --> 08:26.114
I would like to be sure.

08:26.157 --> 08:28.595
Let's give it back
to Dr. Hamamura in peds.

08:28.638 --> 08:30.074
Those symptoms are basically...

08:30.118 --> 08:31.946
Oh!
MOTHER:
Ellie.

08:32.947 --> 08:35.515
Here you go. Ready?
There we go. Sorry.

08:35.558 --> 08:37.255
The findings are nonspecific.

08:37.299 --> 08:39.780
Hence my desire for
more diagnostic testing.

08:39.823 --> 08:40.998
We should have
some answers

08:41.042 --> 08:42.478
for you all very soon.

08:42.522 --> 08:44.741
[busy chatter]

08:46.961 --> 08:48.745
How long are we gonna do this?

08:48.789 --> 08:50.355
You won't make
eye contact with me,

08:50.399 --> 08:52.401
you barely speak to me.What do you want me to say, Lex?

08:52.444 --> 08:55.360
Whatever you need to say
for us to get through this.

08:55.404 --> 08:56.797
[clears throat]

08:58.015 --> 09:00.757
We have always been straight
with each other.

09:00.801 --> 09:03.804
That was before you slept
with my father.

09:04.979 --> 09:06.589
I trusted you.

09:06.633 --> 09:10.158
I confided in you about him.

09:10.201 --> 09:12.639
And this whole time, you...No, not this whole time.

09:12.682 --> 09:15.946
I swear, it just started a few
months before the shooting.

09:15.990 --> 09:17.948
The fact that it started at all.

09:17.992 --> 09:19.515
What is the drama
with them?

09:19.559 --> 09:21.691
I don't know.
Ask Lex.

09:21.735 --> 09:23.084
I did.

09:23.127 --> 09:24.694
She told me to go back
to my hobbit hole,

09:24.738 --> 09:25.956
which makes no sense.

09:26.000 --> 09:27.305
What makes no sense?

09:27.349 --> 09:28.611
Well, hobbits
are famously short,

09:28.655 --> 09:29.786
and they have hairy feet.

09:29.830 --> 09:31.222
I possess neither of
those traits.

09:31.266 --> 09:32.920
You're more hobbit-y
than I am.

09:32.963 --> 09:34.008
Wow, thank you.

09:34.051 --> 09:35.139
What's the holdup?

09:35.183 --> 09:37.011
What are we talking about?
Oh.

09:37.794 --> 09:40.754
Uh, just... feet.

09:40.797 --> 09:42.451
My feet, uh,

09:42.494 --> 09:44.540
which are not hairy.

09:44.584 --> 09:46.629
Not that there's
anything wr...

09:46.673 --> 09:48.065
I mean,
you could have hairy feet,

09:48.109 --> 09:49.893
and that's a beautiful thing.

09:49.937 --> 09:51.547
Wow.

09:51.591 --> 09:53.244
I can't do this right now.

09:53.288 --> 09:54.681
Is that how it's gonna be
from now on?

09:54.724 --> 09:56.726
This is how it's gonna be today.

09:59.729 --> 10:01.731
I've reviewed your chart,
Mr. Morris.

10:01.775 --> 10:03.733
Ted's fine.
Okay.

10:03.777 --> 10:05.256
How long have you had
the palpitations

10:05.300 --> 10:06.780
and the dizziness?Um...

10:06.823 --> 10:09.521
A couple weeks,
but it's-it's getting worse.

10:14.614 --> 10:16.093
That is a rapid heart rate.

10:16.137 --> 10:18.356
I'd like to revisit
the dosages of your medications.

10:18.400 --> 10:19.357
I don't take them.

10:19.401 --> 10:21.055
I don't like pills.

10:21.098 --> 10:22.534
Besides, I, uh,

10:22.578 --> 10:24.101
I pretty much felt fine
up until now, so...

10:24.145 --> 10:26.103
Says you almost passed out
a couple times.

10:26.147 --> 10:27.409
That doesn't sound fine.

10:27.452 --> 10:29.933
Well, I'm just,
I'm tired, you know.

10:29.977 --> 10:31.413
I'm-I'm not
the greatest sleeper.

10:31.456 --> 10:33.241
Well, given your history
of carotid artery disease,

10:33.284 --> 10:35.460
this could be a critical lesion
that needs intervention.

10:35.504 --> 10:37.680
Exactly.
I'd like to admit you.

10:37.724 --> 10:39.682
And-and stay here?

10:39.726 --> 10:41.336
Yes.
Overnight?

10:41.379 --> 10:42.119
Yes.

10:42.163 --> 10:44.469
No way.

10:44.513 --> 10:46.123
Mr. Morris, you may need
to have surgery.

10:46.167 --> 10:47.821
Yeah, you know what?
I-It's fine.

10:47.864 --> 10:48.865
I can always come back tomorrow.

10:48.909 --> 10:49.953
I just, I just
can't sleep here.

10:49.997 --> 10:51.520
Can't sleep at home,
though, either.

10:51.563 --> 10:52.782
Can you?

10:52.826 --> 10:54.044
Given how many times
you're woken up

10:54.088 --> 10:55.437
by your own snoring?

10:55.480 --> 10:57.178
How-how do you know I snore?

10:57.221 --> 10:59.746
Have you lost vision
in an eye recently?

10:59.789 --> 11:01.443
Just for a minute or two?

11:02.226 --> 11:04.359
Yeah, yeah, but I thought
it was a migraine.

11:04.402 --> 11:06.709
Hmm, well,
it wasn't a migraine.

11:06.753 --> 11:07.884
It was a stroke.

11:07.928 --> 11:10.408
Well, a ministroke.

11:10.452 --> 11:13.063
Next time, it'll be
a full cerebrovascular accident.

11:13.107 --> 11:16.893
We're talking, well, paralysis,
speech problems,

11:16.937 --> 11:18.982
brain damage.Wait, I-I didn't...

11:19.026 --> 11:20.723
I didn't tell anybody about
my eye. How do you...

11:20.767 --> 11:22.725
How-how do you know this?

11:22.769 --> 11:24.901
I've been doing this job
a long time, Ted.

11:24.945 --> 11:27.469
Guys like you--
young, don't smoke,

11:27.512 --> 11:29.950
no diabetes, no hypertension,

11:29.993 --> 11:33.605
none of the typical risk factors
for carotid artery disease--

11:33.649 --> 11:36.347
you all snore,
and you're also stubborn,

11:36.391 --> 11:38.959
which means if you've
experienced warning signs,

11:39.002 --> 11:40.743
you ignored them.

11:40.787 --> 11:42.092
It's why guys like you,

11:42.136 --> 11:44.007
who shouldn't even have
this disease,

11:44.051 --> 11:45.748
usually end up dying from it.

11:46.967 --> 11:48.359
But, you know...

11:50.535 --> 11:53.277
♪

11:58.108 --> 11:59.631
Hey, Hamamura.

11:59.675 --> 12:01.633
We got a triple CABG later,
you want it?

12:01.677 --> 12:04.419
Do I want your coronary artery
bypass surgery?

12:04.462 --> 12:07.683
Yeah, you know, I thought
since we were doing your job.

12:07.727 --> 12:10.904
Keeping that baby alive is,
in fact, all of our jobs.

12:10.947 --> 12:13.515
And I'm happy to consult.

12:13.558 --> 12:14.690
I'll be in touch.

12:15.822 --> 12:17.562
[sighs] Okay.

12:17.606 --> 12:20.391
Your proctorship requires that
you comply with my directives,

12:20.435 --> 12:22.959
not question them. It's all in
the guidelines I sent to you.

12:23.003 --> 12:24.831
Mm, about those guidelines...

12:24.874 --> 12:26.136
Surgeon's knots?

12:26.180 --> 12:28.399
Sim Lab?
Isn't that a little remedial?

12:28.443 --> 12:30.227
They're standard benchmarks
for evaluation.

12:30.271 --> 12:31.576
And we can't skip
the baby steps?

12:31.620 --> 12:33.796
No, you can't skip
basic skill assessments.

12:33.840 --> 12:35.711
I thought the goal was
to get me back into surgery.

12:35.755 --> 12:38.322
It is, once you've proven
basic competency.

12:39.454 --> 12:41.325
You're questioning
my basic competency?[groans]

12:41.369 --> 12:44.459
I am saying that you have to

12:44.502 --> 12:46.635
follow the rules
like everybody else.

12:46.678 --> 12:48.811
Studies show that even
two weeks away from surgery

12:48.855 --> 12:50.813
diminishes performance,
and that's for surgeons

12:50.857 --> 12:52.772
who weren't in a coma
for six months.

12:52.815 --> 12:54.295
Accelerating your time line is

12:54.338 --> 12:56.384
just not in the patients'
best interest.

12:56.427 --> 12:58.734
Which one of us just prevented
a patient from walking out?

12:58.778 --> 13:01.302
You can't skip ahead
without putting in the time.

13:01.345 --> 13:02.738
That's funny.

13:02.782 --> 13:04.827
I know a department head
that did exactly that.

13:04.871 --> 13:06.873
♪

13:07.699 --> 13:10.528
ISAN:Do you have
an emergency contact,

13:10.572 --> 13:12.487
since you'll be staying
here overnight?

13:12.530 --> 13:14.271
Yeah, my wife.

13:14.315 --> 13:16.273
Well, my ex-wife.

13:16.317 --> 13:18.841
Well, I only see
an email address.

13:18.885 --> 13:21.496
Um, yeah, that's--
I-I don't know her number.

13:21.539 --> 13:23.019
She, uh, she changed it
when she left.

13:23.890 --> 13:26.718
Sounds like she'd maybe
rather not be contacted.

13:26.762 --> 13:27.545
[chuckles]

13:27.589 --> 13:29.112
She's just mad, you know.

13:29.156 --> 13:30.635
It's just who she is.

13:30.679 --> 13:31.506
[laughs]

13:31.549 --> 13:32.899
How-how long's it been?

13:32.942 --> 13:34.335
How long were we married?

13:34.378 --> 13:35.815
No, how long since she left?

13:36.859 --> 13:38.339
Um...

13:38.382 --> 13:40.167
About eight-eight years.

13:40.210 --> 13:41.472
Give or take.

13:43.518 --> 13:45.694
He doesn't take his meds
for his heart condition.

13:45.737 --> 13:47.391
Doesn't realize his wife's
not coming back.

13:47.435 --> 13:49.002
That's how denial works.

13:49.045 --> 13:51.265
You see what you want to see.
You ignore what you don't.

13:51.308 --> 13:53.528
Where is she going?

13:53.571 --> 13:55.095
[elevator bell dings]Well, if I had to guess,

13:55.138 --> 13:56.226
I'd say she's going out.

13:56.270 --> 13:58.359
With him.

13:58.402 --> 14:00.927
[scoffs] What, like a date?

14:00.970 --> 14:02.406
No. No way.

14:02.450 --> 14:03.973
Hey, Caleb.

14:04.017 --> 14:06.410
What's that you were saying
about denial?

14:08.369 --> 14:09.544
SAM:
I'm not saying

14:09.587 --> 14:10.719
that I wish my dad were

14:10.762 --> 14:12.242
still in a coma.[chuckles]

14:13.461 --> 14:16.072
You're thinking you have had
better conversations

14:16.116 --> 14:17.291
on a first date.

14:17.334 --> 14:18.988
[both chuckle]

14:19.032 --> 14:20.555
Actually, I am thinking about

14:20.598 --> 14:23.775
how beautiful you look
right now.

14:26.082 --> 14:27.518
Well...

14:27.562 --> 14:29.825
[clears throat][laughs]

14:29.869 --> 14:31.131
I am, uh...

14:31.174 --> 14:33.307
better at taking vitals
than taking compliments.

14:33.350 --> 14:34.656
Yeah.

14:34.699 --> 14:36.179
Thank you.

14:36.223 --> 14:38.616
You are welcome.

14:41.141 --> 14:42.142
SERVER:
Right this way.

14:42.185 --> 14:44.796
Yeah. Mm.
Uh-huh.

14:45.972 --> 14:47.277
Okay. [chuckles]

14:47.321 --> 14:48.931
I needed this.

14:48.975 --> 14:52.804
To get out of the hospital,
mentally and physically.

14:52.848 --> 14:56.156
And tonight,
all I want to think about is...

14:56.199 --> 14:57.853
My dad.

14:57.897 --> 14:59.899
Sorry?

14:59.942 --> 15:01.248
My dad is here.

15:01.291 --> 15:02.945
[quiet chatter]

15:03.772 --> 15:05.905
And he's having dinner
with my dad.

15:05.948 --> 15:08.516
SAM:
The chairman of the board.

15:08.559 --> 15:11.127
He's trying to go
over my head.

15:11.171 --> 15:13.782
Skip to the end
of his proctorship.

15:14.739 --> 15:16.785
♪

15:19.831 --> 15:20.920
[sighs]

15:30.016 --> 15:30.973
Hey.

15:31.017 --> 15:32.409
Hi. Ugh.

15:32.453 --> 15:34.585
I'm sorry again
for bailing on you last night.

15:34.629 --> 15:36.674
And I am sorry
for accidentally taking you out

15:36.718 --> 15:38.241
on the worst double date
in history.

15:38.285 --> 15:40.156
[chuckles] It was a long night,

15:40.200 --> 15:42.376
but I am almost done here.

15:43.159 --> 15:44.639
What is all of this?

15:44.682 --> 15:46.293
This is every study I could find
on the value

15:46.336 --> 15:47.772
of empirical assessments
for surgeons

15:47.816 --> 15:50.036
after an extended leave.Hmm.

15:50.079 --> 15:52.081
Before my dad convinces
the board to fast-track him,

15:52.125 --> 15:54.127
I just think they should see
all the data.

15:54.170 --> 15:56.433
This is a lot of data.Yeah.

15:56.477 --> 15:58.131
Which I find to be very, um...

15:58.174 --> 15:59.915
What? Preachy? Pedantic?

15:59.959 --> 16:00.960
Sexy.

16:02.700 --> 16:04.050
Oh.

16:04.093 --> 16:06.095
Data is my love language.

16:06.139 --> 16:08.184
You and me both.

16:08.228 --> 16:10.056
My mom is gonna slip these

16:10.099 --> 16:11.666
to the board
before the meeting.

16:11.709 --> 16:13.189
If they let my dad have his way
and something goes wrong,

16:13.233 --> 16:14.364
they'll have blood
on their hands.

16:14.408 --> 16:16.149
Oh, my God. Okay, you...

16:16.192 --> 16:17.933
You didn't put that in there,
did you?

16:17.977 --> 16:19.761
Not in so many words.

16:19.804 --> 16:21.241
Good. [laughs]

16:21.284 --> 16:22.982
'Cause I'm guessing that
blood on their hands is not

16:23.025 --> 16:24.287
their love language.

16:26.159 --> 16:27.290
SAM:
How are his vitals?

16:27.334 --> 16:29.336
Blood pressure 184/124.

16:29.379 --> 16:30.859
Heart rate in the 120s.

16:30.902 --> 16:32.861
Hmm. Let's increase
his nicardipine drip

16:32.904 --> 16:33.949
and order a beta-blocker.

16:33.993 --> 16:35.559
Why haven't you done
the surgery yet?

16:35.603 --> 16:38.127
You have to be medically
optimized for surgery,

16:38.171 --> 16:39.215
and that can take some time,

16:39.259 --> 16:40.608
especially
since you didn't take

16:40.651 --> 16:42.523
your prescribed
anticoagulants.

16:42.566 --> 16:43.785
Can't you just do it?

16:43.828 --> 16:45.004
Well, I...Dr. Griffith can't

16:45.047 --> 16:46.179
perform surgery right now.

16:46.222 --> 16:48.050
Why not?He's undergoing proctorship.

16:48.094 --> 16:49.356
GRIFF:
I'll be hands-on.

16:49.399 --> 16:50.618
I'll supervise
the whole time.

16:50.661 --> 16:52.054
In a completely hands-off
kind of way.

16:52.098 --> 16:53.882
Look, I just, I just want
to get this over with.

16:53.925 --> 16:54.883
SAM:
I understand.

16:54.926 --> 16:56.537
But there is a reason

16:56.580 --> 16:58.539
that we do things this way.

16:58.582 --> 16:59.888
We want to reduce your risk

16:59.931 --> 17:02.064
and increase
your chances of success.

17:02.108 --> 17:03.326
And so, cutting corners

17:03.370 --> 17:05.285
or rushing the process

17:05.328 --> 17:07.200
would not be a good idea.

17:07.243 --> 17:09.463
No matter what the board says.

17:09.506 --> 17:10.768
[baby coughing]

17:10.812 --> 17:12.770
There's the enlargement we saw
on the X-ray.

17:12.814 --> 17:15.556
The muscle tissue in the left
ventricle is very thick.

17:15.599 --> 17:16.861
The word is "hypertrophic."

17:16.905 --> 17:18.863
SAM: His heart
muscle is enlarged,

17:18.907 --> 17:19.734
which can cause

17:19.777 --> 17:21.127
a fluid backup in his lungs.

17:21.170 --> 17:22.258
It might explain the...

17:22.302 --> 17:24.086
[machine beeping][coughing]

17:24.130 --> 17:25.827
Page Respiratory for me now.[baby crying]

17:25.870 --> 17:27.698
Why don't we step
outside, please?

17:27.742 --> 17:29.700
Why? What's going on?Let's go down
to the cafe.

17:29.744 --> 17:32.007
[beeping rapidly]What...

17:32.051 --> 17:33.487
Baby's in V-tach.What's wrong with him?

17:33.530 --> 17:35.010
Crash cart! Cart!What's wrong with him?

17:35.054 --> 17:36.925
Get me the pace pads,
I need to shock him out of it.

17:36.968 --> 17:38.144
GRIFF:
We need you to step outside.

17:38.187 --> 17:39.971
I'm not going.[beeping steadies]

17:40.015 --> 17:41.321
[baby coughs]

17:41.364 --> 17:43.410
[baby fusses]Spontaneously converted.

17:43.453 --> 17:44.715
Get him on an ACE inhibitor.

17:44.759 --> 17:46.413
I want an MRI as soon
as anesthesia can do it.

17:46.456 --> 17:47.631
I don't understand.

17:47.675 --> 17:49.372
He had an arrhythmia.What caused that?

17:49.416 --> 17:50.982
That is what
we're gonna find out.

18:03.343 --> 18:05.388
[door opens]

18:06.955 --> 18:08.391
Hey.
Hey.

18:08.435 --> 18:10.741
Thanks for coming.Well, you said

18:10.785 --> 18:13.048
that if I met you,
you would stop texting me.

18:13.092 --> 18:15.268
Uh-uh-uh.

18:16.225 --> 18:17.792
Just so we are clear,

18:17.835 --> 18:19.663
whatever we used to do in here,

18:19.707 --> 18:21.970
we're not doing it now.

18:22.013 --> 18:24.364
You have to stop this.

18:24.407 --> 18:27.454
Don't you miss us?

18:29.064 --> 18:30.979
No.

18:33.112 --> 18:35.723
I'm past this.

18:35.766 --> 18:38.247
Okay? And you need to be, too.

18:38.291 --> 18:40.162
I'm trying.

18:40.206 --> 18:42.512
I need time. It's...

18:42.556 --> 18:46.081
It's been six months for you,
not for me.

18:46.125 --> 18:48.214
It's been six months
for everyone, Griff.

18:49.040 --> 18:50.651
You know, but you don't
want to accept it

18:50.694 --> 18:53.001
because in your head,
you're still there--

18:53.044 --> 18:54.611
before you were shot,

18:54.655 --> 18:57.179
before Sam took over,
before we broke up.

18:57.223 --> 18:59.312
It was good back then, though.

18:59.355 --> 19:00.704
Wasn't it?

19:00.748 --> 19:03.446
We cannot go back
to the way it was.

19:03.490 --> 19:05.448
So...

19:05.492 --> 19:08.364
No more texting.
No more calling.

19:08.408 --> 19:10.671
And no more looking at me
the way you do.

19:10.714 --> 19:12.760
I like looking at you.

19:12.803 --> 19:14.370
Well, you need to quit.

19:14.414 --> 19:16.633
[sighs] Look,
it's in the past,

19:16.677 --> 19:19.288
and that's where it has to stay.

19:21.247 --> 19:23.031
[door opens]

19:32.519 --> 19:33.998
What are you doing?

19:34.042 --> 19:35.783
Uh, nothing.
Really?

19:35.826 --> 19:38.351
Because it looks like
you were in the supply closet

19:38.394 --> 19:41.049
racking up HR violations.Well, technically,

19:41.092 --> 19:43.399
it's not a violation because
I'm no longer a supervisor.

19:43.443 --> 19:46.663
Oh, my...Where am I supposed to have
a private conversation?

19:46.707 --> 19:48.187
My office is occupied.

19:48.230 --> 19:50.145
It's not your office,
and you are not in charge.

19:50.189 --> 19:53.583
Hey, why were you having dinner
with Byron Kingsley last night?

19:53.627 --> 19:56.325
Because I needed to talk to him,
and, again, no office.

19:56.369 --> 19:59.372
Do you know why Sam was given
this job, Griff?

19:59.415 --> 20:00.286
Because I was in a coma?

20:00.329 --> 20:01.722
Because she was the best.

20:01.765 --> 20:03.593
A lot of people went
up for that position.

20:03.637 --> 20:05.769
She was the best candidate.

20:05.813 --> 20:07.031
I'm sure she was,
compared to them,

20:07.075 --> 20:08.250
but not compared to me.

20:08.294 --> 20:10.078
[groans]We both know I should be

20:10.121 --> 20:12.907
back in charge
and back in surgery.

20:12.950 --> 20:14.213
You want to get
back in surgery?

20:14.256 --> 20:16.389
Then get out
of the closet

20:16.432 --> 20:19.305
and focus
on your proctorship.

20:19.348 --> 20:20.958
Oh, I'm very focused. I'm on it.

20:21.002 --> 20:23.613
In fact,
I got a meeting right now.

20:24.397 --> 20:28.314
What meeting?
Proctees don't have meetings.

20:28.357 --> 20:30.751
Can't hear you.

20:31.578 --> 20:33.406
SAM:
I don't get it.
A ten-month-old

20:33.449 --> 20:35.103
with left ventricular
hypertrophy,

20:35.146 --> 20:36.583
and his cough
is getting worse

20:36.626 --> 20:37.584
despite the meds.

20:37.627 --> 20:39.455
Maybe it's because of the meds?

20:39.499 --> 20:40.804
Side effect of
the ACE inhibitor.

20:40.848 --> 20:42.153
It's possible.
We can switch him

20:42.197 --> 20:43.590
to irbesartan.GRIFF: Put him on irbesartan.

20:43.633 --> 20:45.113
Yeah, that thing.

20:45.156 --> 20:46.027
Sorry. Go ahead.

20:46.070 --> 20:47.420
And we'll put him on a diuretic

20:47.463 --> 20:49.335
to address the fluid
built-up in him lungs.

20:49.378 --> 20:51.772
[cell phone ringing]

20:51.815 --> 20:53.643
[clears throat]

20:53.687 --> 20:54.644
Whose phone is that?

20:54.688 --> 20:56.472
It's unprofessional.

20:56.516 --> 20:58.735
[ringing continues]

21:00.346 --> 21:01.869
Oh. [chuckles]

21:01.912 --> 21:02.957
[fake chuckle]

21:03.000 --> 21:04.915
Here, hold that.

21:06.090 --> 21:08.136
It's me.

21:08.179 --> 21:11.792
And I have to take it.
Excuse me.

21:11.835 --> 21:14.838
♪

21:14.882 --> 21:16.405
You tell her I say hi.

21:16.449 --> 21:18.842
Okay. I got to go.

21:18.886 --> 21:22.803
We have an infant undergoing
diagnostic testing.

21:22.846 --> 21:24.500
You cannot take a phone call.

21:24.544 --> 21:25.675
I understand.I don't think you do.

21:25.719 --> 21:28.069
You are under my authority.

21:28.112 --> 21:30.332
I dictate
how this proctorship proceeds,

21:30.376 --> 21:33.117
no matter how many members
of the board you take to dinner.

21:33.161 --> 21:34.597
They concur.

21:34.641 --> 21:35.946
Who is they?The board.

21:35.990 --> 21:37.121
They just called.

21:37.165 --> 21:38.688
They agree with you
on the time line.

21:38.732 --> 21:39.994
No fast-tracking.

21:40.037 --> 21:42.692
This proctorship ends
when you say it ends.

21:42.736 --> 21:44.738
Oh. Well,

21:44.781 --> 21:45.956
good.

21:46.000 --> 21:47.567
They-they did also agree
with me

21:47.610 --> 21:49.264
that when it ends,

21:49.308 --> 21:52.659
I'll be reinstated as chief.What?

21:52.702 --> 21:54.617
GRIFF:
I get my job back.

21:54.661 --> 21:56.706
Things go back
to how they were,

21:56.750 --> 21:58.447
and...

21:58.491 --> 22:00.275
how they ought to be.

22:00.319 --> 22:02.886
♪

22:13.157 --> 22:15.899
♪

22:16.726 --> 22:19.599
If I wasn't so angry,
I'd be impressed.

22:19.642 --> 22:21.252
How did he do this?

22:21.296 --> 22:22.950
How could the board have
agreed to it?

22:22.993 --> 22:24.778
What did he say to them?Yeah, I-I don't know.

22:24.821 --> 22:26.301
I wasn't there, but, uh...

22:26.345 --> 22:27.955
The chief medical officer
doesn't get invited

22:27.998 --> 22:30.784
to board meetings,
but he gets a seat at the table.

22:30.827 --> 22:32.438
VIVIAN:
He should never
have been allowed

22:32.481 --> 22:33.352
in that room.

22:33.395 --> 22:34.527
But he was.

22:34.570 --> 22:37.094
♪

22:38.922 --> 22:40.881
What am I supposed to do now?

22:40.924 --> 22:43.144
You don't have to proctor him.

22:43.187 --> 22:44.841
He'll just find
someone else to do it.

22:44.885 --> 22:47.409
Until you clear him,

22:47.453 --> 22:49.846
he answers to you.

22:49.890 --> 22:51.413
And then what?
He gets his job back?

22:51.457 --> 22:53.110
No, he can't just
get it back.

22:53.154 --> 22:54.721
They have to formally vote
on it.

22:54.764 --> 22:56.331
Without hearing my side?

22:56.375 --> 22:58.072
They can't do that.
I have to get in front of them.

22:58.115 --> 23:00.074
Well, they've already adjourned,
but...
Well, then

23:00.117 --> 23:02.424
I'll call an emergency meeting.

23:02.468 --> 23:05.122
If he found a way to get
into that room, so can I.

23:05.862 --> 23:08.125
♪

23:10.389 --> 23:12.042
[groans]

23:12.086 --> 23:14.393
I am so much happier
working for Sam.

23:14.436 --> 23:16.525
Griff getting his job back
is not good for me.

23:16.569 --> 23:18.701
You're right.
He never liked you.Have you seen Ted's labs?

23:18.745 --> 23:20.268
His blood sugar is
through the roof.

23:20.311 --> 23:22.139
He's afebrile.
Troponins are negative.

23:22.183 --> 23:23.532
Could just be a stress response.

23:23.576 --> 23:25.186
Or he's sneaking food in.

23:25.229 --> 23:26.448
They all do it.

23:26.492 --> 23:27.841
These delivery apps?

23:27.884 --> 23:30.234
Yesterday, I intercepted
a Coney dog with fries.

23:30.278 --> 23:31.758
We need the
evidence, Donna.

23:31.801 --> 23:32.802
I'm on it.

23:32.846 --> 23:34.761
[groans]

23:34.804 --> 23:36.545
Would you relax?

23:36.589 --> 23:38.591
[scoffs] Sam is still the boss.

23:38.634 --> 23:40.114
Just follow her lead.

23:40.157 --> 23:41.550
I agree.

23:41.594 --> 23:42.725
Because you're trying to get
back together with her.

23:42.769 --> 23:43.987
Oh, that ship has sailed.

23:44.031 --> 23:45.902
Wrong, it hasn't
sailed at all.

23:45.946 --> 23:48.557
I know that ship well.
It's a very reliable vessel.

23:48.601 --> 23:50.603
You do know Sam is not
a boat, right?

23:50.646 --> 23:52.735
The relationship's the boat.And it's still in the harbor.

23:52.779 --> 23:54.258
It's halfway to Fiji.

23:54.302 --> 23:56.957
[panting]:
Griff can't be our boss again.

23:57.000 --> 23:58.915
I think I'm having
a panic attack.

23:58.959 --> 24:00.526
Lex, take my pulse.

24:00.569 --> 24:02.136
You've lost your damn mind.

24:02.179 --> 24:03.180
Look,

24:03.224 --> 24:05.008
we follow Sam.

24:05.052 --> 24:07.141
All right? Don't get caught up
in Griff's game.

24:09.143 --> 24:10.449
Let's go.

24:12.538 --> 24:14.931
SAM:
Okay, back to
our pediatric case.

24:14.975 --> 24:16.846
MRI shows the muscle
in the left ventricle

24:16.890 --> 24:18.152
is not only thick,
it's filled

24:18.195 --> 24:19.936
with deep
intertrabecular recesses.

24:19.980 --> 24:21.764
The myocardium looks
like a sponge.

24:21.808 --> 24:23.897
It looks, I don't know,
embryonic?

24:23.940 --> 24:25.812
Exactly, undeveloped cells
that contribute

24:25.855 --> 24:27.291
nothing to the overall
heart function.

24:27.335 --> 24:28.945
GRIFF:Dr. Shah,
I'd like to follow up

24:28.989 --> 24:30.643
on this mitral valve
replacement.

24:31.078 --> 24:33.950
Follow up with me?
Yeah.

24:33.994 --> 24:35.561
I need you to get a PFT,

24:35.604 --> 24:36.692
please.

24:36.736 --> 24:39.086
Dr. Shah, stop right there.

24:39.129 --> 24:40.914
No one should be
ordering tests for

24:40.957 --> 24:43.046
or taking cases
from Dr. Griffith.

24:43.090 --> 24:44.526
The board's decision is not

24:44.570 --> 24:46.136
immediately effective.

24:46.180 --> 24:47.964
We are discussing
this infant's treatment plan.

24:48.008 --> 24:50.227
Put him on the transplant list,
prepare for a Berlin Heart.

24:50.271 --> 24:52.708
There, now can we talk about
my thing?

24:52.752 --> 24:54.493
SAM:
A transplant is not
his only option.

24:54.536 --> 24:56.756
This is a genetic disorder.For which there is no cure.

24:56.799 --> 24:58.540
A lot of major
academic institutions

24:58.584 --> 25:01.151
are making huge achievements
in gene editing therapy.

25:01.195 --> 25:03.545
Which holds a lot of promise
for the future, but not today.

25:03.589 --> 25:04.720
Not for this patient.

25:04.764 --> 25:06.287
Just because
something is new

25:06.330 --> 25:08.158
and different does not
automatically disqualify it

25:08.202 --> 25:09.769
as a valid--Huntington's. Sickle cell.

25:09.812 --> 25:11.640
Hemophilia.
All caused by an alteration

25:11.684 --> 25:12.815
to a single nucleotide.

25:12.859 --> 25:14.513
Mm-hmm.How do we know which one?

25:14.556 --> 25:15.775
Dr. Costa.

25:15.818 --> 25:17.341
We mapped the genomes
of patients

25:17.385 --> 25:19.430
with those diseases
and found the common mutations.

25:19.474 --> 25:21.389
Which requires what?

25:22.651 --> 25:24.000
Dr. Shah?

25:24.044 --> 25:26.307
A big enough sample size

25:26.350 --> 25:28.135
of affected patients
to draw comparisons.

25:28.178 --> 25:30.224
There are over 50 genes
affecting heart development.

25:30.267 --> 25:32.269
Even if we mapped
the baby's genome,

25:32.313 --> 25:33.923
even if we found the mutations,

25:33.967 --> 25:36.099
we would have no way of knowing
which one caused the disease.

25:36.143 --> 25:39.581
A sample size of one is
simply too small.

25:39.625 --> 25:41.627
♪

25:43.193 --> 25:45.239
[wrapper rustling]

25:45.282 --> 25:46.719
What you got there, Ted?

25:46.762 --> 25:48.547
Huh? Nothing.LEX: Really?

25:48.590 --> 25:50.897
Because Donna says she saw some
candy wrappers in here earlier.

25:50.940 --> 25:51.985
Gummy bears.

25:52.028 --> 25:53.247
Under the pillow.

25:53.290 --> 25:54.814
You can't eat
before surgery, Ted,

25:54.857 --> 25:56.250
especially not candy.

25:56.293 --> 25:57.294
Why not?

25:57.338 --> 25:58.426
LEX:
Because high blood sugar causes

25:58.469 --> 25:59.949
something called
oxidative stress,

25:59.993 --> 26:01.603
which will damage
your blood vessels

26:01.647 --> 26:03.170
and increase
your risk of stroke.

26:03.213 --> 26:05.520
And risk of stroke is why
you're here in the first place.

26:05.564 --> 26:06.913
But we can't do your procedure

26:06.956 --> 26:08.523
until you're
medically optimized.

26:08.567 --> 26:09.916
What does that mean?

26:09.959 --> 26:12.527
That means you just
delayed your surgery.

26:12.571 --> 26:14.268
You mean I got to stay here
longer?

26:14.311 --> 26:15.574
Yep.

26:15.617 --> 26:17.184
Well, can I at least have
a new nurse, then?

26:17.227 --> 26:18.881
No, Ted.

26:19.752 --> 26:22.015
♪

26:22.929 --> 26:24.670
SAM:
We will monitor his heart.

26:24.713 --> 26:27.194
And there are medications
that can help with his symptoms,

26:27.237 --> 26:28.761
but he will likely be
on them

26:28.804 --> 26:30.284
for the rest of his life.

26:30.327 --> 26:32.112
[baby coughs]What do you think?

26:32.155 --> 26:33.896
Uh...
There are potential
treatment options

26:33.940 --> 26:35.202
that we would like to discuss.

26:35.245 --> 26:37.204
We want what's best
for our kids, don't we?

26:37.247 --> 26:39.075
Sometimes, that means
making difficult decisions

26:39.119 --> 26:41.469
that they just don't understand.

26:41.512 --> 26:42.905
Thank you, Doctor.
FATHER:
Wait.

26:42.949 --> 26:44.559
Difficult decisions?
What do you mean?

26:44.603 --> 26:46.126
Gene therapy is one of
the options...

26:46.169 --> 26:47.954
He's gonna need
a Berlin Heart.

26:49.738 --> 26:52.436
That looks like life support.

26:52.480 --> 26:54.003
It is heart support,

26:54.047 --> 26:55.875
but he'll be breathing

26:55.918 --> 26:57.572
on his own.

26:57.616 --> 26:59.008
It's just a stopgap measure

26:59.052 --> 27:01.445
while he awaits
a heart transplant.

27:01.489 --> 27:03.186
A heart transplant?

27:03.230 --> 27:04.797
[groans]

27:04.840 --> 27:06.059
That was out of line.

27:06.102 --> 27:07.538
It's the next logical step.

27:07.582 --> 27:09.236
I have barely finished
walking those parents

27:09.279 --> 27:11.064
through the diagnosis,
and you are talking about

27:11.107 --> 27:12.892
plugging their child
into a machine.

27:12.935 --> 27:14.720
It's a pediatric
ventricular assist device,

27:14.763 --> 27:16.069
but yes.

27:16.112 --> 27:17.461
It's designed for
end-stage heart failure.

27:17.505 --> 27:19.072
Now is not the time
for that conversation.

27:19.115 --> 27:20.160
Given his rate
of decompensation,

27:20.203 --> 27:21.552
it is precisely the time.

27:21.596 --> 27:22.728
In your opinion.

27:22.771 --> 27:24.294
In my experience,
which we both know

27:24.338 --> 27:26.427
vastly outweighs yours.Yes, it does.

27:26.470 --> 27:28.908
And in this case,
your approach is outdated.

27:28.951 --> 27:30.823
Look, space medicine is not
gonna help that baby.

27:30.866 --> 27:31.824
Gene therapy has helped

27:31.867 --> 27:33.652
a lot of people.

27:33.695 --> 27:35.349
Look, Dad,
I understand

27:35.392 --> 27:37.133
that you want to go back to
a time where you were in charge

27:37.177 --> 27:38.700
and dinosaurs roamed the Earth.

27:38.744 --> 27:39.962
Ouch.But things change.

27:40.006 --> 27:41.268
Meteorites hit,

27:41.311 --> 27:43.052
and a species
that fails to evolve

27:43.096 --> 27:44.793
renders itself extinct.

27:44.837 --> 27:46.447
Speciesevolve

27:46.490 --> 27:48.449
by learning from experience.[groans] Okay.

27:48.492 --> 27:50.190
I am not giving up
on that baby.

27:50.233 --> 27:52.932
Those parents would give
anything to help their child,

27:52.975 --> 27:54.673
which I know you can't relate to
as a father.

27:54.716 --> 27:57.153
Wow. I thought we were talking
as doctors.

27:57.197 --> 27:58.894
Are we getting personal now?

27:58.938 --> 28:00.635
Well, you make
it hard not to.

28:00.679 --> 28:02.550
So, what are we talking about?

28:02.593 --> 28:04.465
The job? Lex? Or...

28:04.508 --> 28:07.947
[scoffs] We are talking about
you and your ego

28:07.990 --> 28:10.776
making it impossible
for me to do my job.

28:10.819 --> 28:12.778
I'm trying to help.
I'm trying to help the patient.

28:12.821 --> 28:14.344
Trying to help you.

28:14.388 --> 28:15.868
Trying to help the hospital.You want to help the patient?

28:15.911 --> 28:17.652
Don't undermine
my treatment strategy.

28:18.305 --> 28:19.480
And since you bought up Lex,

28:19.523 --> 28:20.742
the next time
you want to help me,

28:20.786 --> 28:22.831
don't screw my best friend!

28:23.919 --> 28:26.705
♪

28:35.322 --> 28:37.063
Lex, I'm sorry.

28:37.106 --> 28:39.282
I don't want your apology
any more than you want mine.

28:39.326 --> 28:41.023
It's not gonna change anything.

28:41.067 --> 28:42.721
I didn't mean
to out you like that.

28:42.764 --> 28:45.724
I don't want to make this harder
than it already is.

28:45.767 --> 28:47.551
LEX:
Too late.

28:53.906 --> 28:56.299
I don't know what it's gonna
take to make this better,

28:56.343 --> 28:59.302
but I know it's bigger
than "sorry."

29:02.218 --> 29:03.437
[elevator bell dings]

29:03.480 --> 29:05.221
Dr. Tucker,
I need you to prepare

29:05.265 --> 29:06.614
a surgical consent form

29:06.657 --> 29:08.398
for putting a patient
on a Berlin Heart. Here.

29:08.442 --> 29:10.096
For the pediatric case?

29:10.139 --> 29:11.880
Is there another patient
in imminent need

29:11.924 --> 29:13.577
of an assist device?

29:13.621 --> 29:15.362
Is Dr. Griffith aware that
we're moving forward...

29:15.405 --> 29:18.234
It's a timely request, Doctor.Right.

29:18.278 --> 29:19.758
I'm on it.

29:22.630 --> 29:25.067
What happened to
"follow Sam's lead"?[elevator bell dings]

29:25.111 --> 29:26.503
What was I supposed to do?

29:26.547 --> 29:28.592
Dr. Tucker, we have a problem.

29:28.636 --> 29:30.159
No kidding.It's Ted.

29:30.203 --> 29:33.249
Those were not
ordinary gummy bears.

29:33.293 --> 29:34.990
TED:
Somebody call 911!

29:35.034 --> 29:36.470
What is going on?

29:36.513 --> 29:38.689
I'm-I'm having a heart attack.He was eating candy,

29:38.733 --> 29:40.604
again, when I checked on him
this morning.

29:40.648 --> 29:42.519
This time,
when I confiscated it,

29:42.563 --> 29:45.044
I took a better look
at the container.

29:45.087 --> 29:48.090
Edible cannabis.
He's stoned?

29:48.134 --> 29:50.876
Ah, rapid heart rate,
disorientation...

29:50.919 --> 29:52.138
I'm dying, and-and...

29:52.181 --> 29:53.095
she's trying to kill me.And paranoia.

29:53.139 --> 29:54.227
Yeah, very stoned.

29:54.270 --> 29:55.968
How many of these
did you eat?

29:56.011 --> 29:58.579
Dr. Trulie,
he ate them all.

29:58.622 --> 29:59.928
Let's increase
his maintenance fluids

29:59.972 --> 30:01.625
to help flush out his system.
It'll be a while

30:01.669 --> 30:03.149
before anesthesia touches him.

30:03.192 --> 30:05.281
You just delayed
your surgery again, Ted.

30:05.325 --> 30:06.935
Uh...

30:09.677 --> 30:11.722
♪

30:16.902 --> 30:19.687
I see that you got consent
for the Berlin device.

30:20.993 --> 30:22.211
It was the right call.

30:22.255 --> 30:24.170
I just hope
it doesn't come to that.

30:24.213 --> 30:25.911
Griff had me do it.

30:25.954 --> 30:29.610
Yeah, he can be very persuasive.
Just ask the board.

30:29.653 --> 30:31.960
Have you tried talking to them

30:32.004 --> 30:33.614
about his reinstatement?
Yeah.

30:33.657 --> 30:35.659
I've tried, but
only department heads can call

30:35.703 --> 30:37.487
a meeting with the board,
and apparently,

30:37.531 --> 30:39.881
in light of yesterday's
decision, I'm interim head.

30:39.925 --> 30:41.361
So...
Like I said,

30:41.404 --> 30:42.928
he can be very persuasive.

30:42.971 --> 30:46.496
Well, I-I, uh, did some research
into pediatric gene therapy.

30:46.540 --> 30:49.021
So, Boston Children's
has multiple trials

30:49.064 --> 30:51.153
trying to tackle
congenital cardiac disorders.

30:51.197 --> 30:52.676
I sent them an email.

30:52.720 --> 30:53.808
Really?

30:53.852 --> 30:55.114
And if there are
other patients out there

30:55.157 --> 30:56.376
who have his disease,

30:56.419 --> 30:57.638
it could get you
the sample size you need.

30:57.681 --> 30:59.727
I really appreciate that.

30:59.770 --> 31:01.337
Even if it's a long shot,
it's...

31:01.381 --> 31:02.773
Better than giving up.

31:02.817 --> 31:05.385
♪

31:06.560 --> 31:07.909
Thank you, Caleb.What can I say?

31:07.953 --> 31:09.563
I'm a sucker for the underdog.

31:09.606 --> 31:11.565
[devices beeping][groans]

31:11.608 --> 31:13.175
The baby.

31:13.219 --> 31:14.481
And Ted.

31:15.264 --> 31:17.005
Oxygen sats are dropping.

31:17.049 --> 31:18.615
Cardiac output is down.

31:18.659 --> 31:20.922
We need to get him
to the OR now.What's happening?

31:20.966 --> 31:22.445
His heart is failing.

31:22.489 --> 31:24.012
We need to place him
on the Berlin device now.

31:24.056 --> 31:26.493
♪

31:26.536 --> 31:28.495
[steady beeping]What's going on with Ted?

31:28.538 --> 31:30.932
Started slurring his speech,
said his face felt numb.

31:30.976 --> 31:32.238
Ischemic stroke.

31:32.281 --> 31:34.066
So much for medically
optimizing him.

31:34.109 --> 31:35.676
How long has it been?

31:35.719 --> 31:36.764
Couple minutes.

31:36.807 --> 31:37.939
That's a lot of brain cells.

31:37.983 --> 31:39.245
NEUROSURGEON:
I'm accessing

31:39.288 --> 31:40.159
the internal carotid artery
right now.

31:40.202 --> 31:42.813
[rapid beeping]

31:47.079 --> 31:48.297
Shunt is in.

31:49.385 --> 31:51.300
Come on, Ted.

31:51.344 --> 31:53.346
[beeping steadies][sighs] Okay.

31:53.389 --> 31:55.478
Thank God.
Let's clean this up.

31:56.349 --> 31:57.959
GRIFF:Make sure they give him
the unfractionated heparin

31:58.003 --> 31:59.352
immediately.I know.

31:59.395 --> 32:01.180
Deterioration of the filling
behavior may indicate

32:01.223 --> 32:02.790
hypovolemia, obstruction
of the inflow cannula.

32:02.833 --> 32:05.010
I know that, too.Well, atrial cannulation

32:05.053 --> 32:06.968
definitely can be a lot harder
than you anticipate.

32:07.012 --> 32:08.491
Stop.You have to get up--

32:08.535 --> 32:10.058
I cannot do this
with you breathing down my neck.

32:10.493 --> 32:11.799
This is as far as you go.

32:16.978 --> 32:18.371
Suction.
Suction.

32:18.414 --> 32:19.981
Good, let's turn it.
Mm-hmm.

32:20.025 --> 32:21.548
15 blade.

32:26.335 --> 32:27.684
I should be in there.

32:27.728 --> 32:29.208
No, she can handle this.

32:29.251 --> 32:31.688
And you would've kicked
yourself out for far less.

32:32.733 --> 32:33.952
[takes deep breath]SAM: Annular.

32:35.954 --> 32:37.303
All right.

32:37.346 --> 32:38.652
[muttering]

32:41.742 --> 32:43.657
[groans softly] Dammit.

32:43.700 --> 32:45.050
It's not threading.

32:45.093 --> 32:46.355
I need to try again.

32:49.750 --> 32:51.012
Push it.

32:51.056 --> 32:52.709
[monitors beeping]

32:52.753 --> 32:54.363
Decreasing cardiac output.Perfusion pressures
are dropping.

32:54.407 --> 32:55.625
I got to get this thing
in before he codes.

32:55.669 --> 32:56.757
Should we call Dr. Griffith?

32:56.800 --> 32:59.803
Jodie, I am Dr. Griffith.
15 blade.

33:00.848 --> 33:03.242
[beeping rapidly]

33:10.466 --> 33:13.165
♪

33:13.208 --> 33:14.644
Start bypass, Dr. Costa.

33:14.688 --> 33:16.690
Starting bypass.

33:17.604 --> 33:19.823
[beeping stops]Low flow.

33:19.867 --> 33:20.868
[sighs]

33:20.911 --> 33:22.783
[sighs]
Okay.

33:22.826 --> 33:23.784
There you go.

33:23.827 --> 33:25.220
You did it.

33:26.265 --> 33:28.441
That'll be all, Jodie.

33:28.484 --> 33:29.833
The procedure just started.

33:29.877 --> 33:31.748
Mm-hmm. Clamp.

33:34.708 --> 33:37.580
There you go.
Clamp the aorta.

33:37.624 --> 33:40.279
Start cardioplegia.
What's she waiting for?

33:40.322 --> 33:42.629
You can't keep doing this.

33:42.672 --> 33:45.110
You are sinking
your relationship with her.

33:45.153 --> 33:47.112
I'm doing this
for our relationship.

33:47.155 --> 33:48.461
Things will get better

33:48.504 --> 33:50.028
when the natural order
is restored.

33:50.071 --> 33:51.072
Better for whom?

33:51.116 --> 33:52.508
For both of us.

33:53.335 --> 33:56.469
She's not ready for all this.

33:56.512 --> 33:58.601
She needs me
more than she thinks.

33:58.645 --> 33:59.994
Not right now,
she doesn't.

34:00.038 --> 34:02.214
And if you don't want to
find yourself locked out

34:02.257 --> 34:03.954
of every surgery
from now on,

34:03.998 --> 34:07.349
find a way to get on board
with this proctorship.

34:11.049 --> 34:13.225
Hey.Hi.

34:13.268 --> 34:14.443
You ready?Yeah.

34:14.487 --> 34:16.663
How'd it go with the baby?He made it.

34:16.706 --> 34:18.186
It was...

34:18.230 --> 34:20.884
complicated, and we're still
waiting for a transplant,

34:20.928 --> 34:22.582
but the procedure went well.

34:22.625 --> 34:24.410
And I did it without my dad.

34:24.453 --> 34:26.107
Where was he?I locked him out.

34:26.151 --> 34:27.587
[laughs]

34:27.630 --> 34:29.719
You locked your father
out of surgery?

34:29.763 --> 34:30.764
Yeah.

34:30.807 --> 34:32.026
He made me do it.

34:32.070 --> 34:33.680
Oh.He...

34:33.723 --> 34:35.769
Mm-mm. We're doing it again.Yes.

34:35.812 --> 34:37.423
Yes, we are.Is there no way for you and I

34:37.466 --> 34:39.512
to go on a date
without our dads ruining it?

34:39.555 --> 34:42.602
No, there-there is...

34:42.645 --> 34:45.083
uh, if we start at the end.

34:45.126 --> 34:48.260
♪

34:55.615 --> 34:59.619
You know, I once read that
a ten-second kiss can result

34:59.662 --> 35:02.100
in the transfer
of 80 million microbes.

35:02.926 --> 35:06.104
Did you just tell me...
dirty data?

35:06.147 --> 35:07.801
It gets dirtier.

35:07.844 --> 35:08.845
[chuckles]

35:08.889 --> 35:10.456
Come on.

35:14.242 --> 35:16.462
♪

35:33.870 --> 35:35.611
Hi.

35:35.655 --> 35:37.178
Were you guys here all night?

35:37.222 --> 35:38.397
Yeah, we didn't want
to leave him alone

35:38.440 --> 35:39.572
his first night on the machine.

35:39.615 --> 35:41.139
I'm about to take Ellie home

35:41.182 --> 35:42.270
to get some sleep.

35:42.314 --> 35:44.229
Hey, can I help you with that?

35:44.272 --> 35:45.360
Come here.

35:45.404 --> 35:48.581
Where is the one
for this foot?

35:48.624 --> 35:49.973
[giggles]

35:52.411 --> 35:55.153
♪

36:00.549 --> 36:02.943
I need to run some tests on her.

36:02.986 --> 36:04.031
On Ellie?

36:05.467 --> 36:06.686
Peripheral edema.

36:06.729 --> 36:08.122
GRIFF:
Due to reduced
systolic function.

36:08.166 --> 36:09.123
Great minds.

36:09.167 --> 36:10.211
I presume you ordered
a diuretic.

36:10.255 --> 36:11.604
And a vasodilator.

36:11.647 --> 36:13.083
But what we really need is...A DNA test.

36:13.127 --> 36:14.911
JOEY: What is going on?The baby's sister.

36:14.955 --> 36:16.478
The reason she doesn't like
to wear shoes.

36:16.522 --> 36:17.740
It's a symptom.

36:17.784 --> 36:19.133
Wait, of the same disease
her brother has?

36:19.177 --> 36:20.961
Less severe, of course,
but two siblings

36:21.004 --> 36:22.310
with the same genetic disorder?Yes.

36:22.354 --> 36:23.964
That's a sample size
we can work with.

36:24.007 --> 36:25.139
We can map the genomes.

36:25.183 --> 36:27.010
Find the mutations.And fix it.

36:27.054 --> 36:28.708
Well...We need a DNA test right away.

36:28.751 --> 36:29.970
If we're right,

36:30.013 --> 36:31.101
this could change
everything for them.

36:31.145 --> 36:32.190
Yeah.

36:32.233 --> 36:34.235
I was wrong
to dismiss gene therapy

36:34.279 --> 36:35.671
and to undermine you.

36:35.715 --> 36:37.107
This is your department,

36:37.151 --> 36:39.806
and I am happy to respect that.

36:39.849 --> 36:41.895
Thank you.

36:41.938 --> 36:45.028
For the next 87 days.87 days?

36:45.072 --> 36:48.031
Which is when the board will
vote to reinstate me.

36:48.075 --> 36:50.033
Assuming I've proven
my basic competency

36:50.077 --> 36:51.774
to your satisfaction.

36:51.818 --> 36:54.299
Which reminds me,
I got, um...

36:54.342 --> 36:56.214
Surgeon's knots.

36:56.257 --> 36:57.476
Mm...

36:57.519 --> 36:58.694
Single knots.

36:59.608 --> 37:02.002
Double knots, and I even
threw in some granny knots.

37:03.003 --> 37:05.527
So, I think that should
check that off the list,

37:05.571 --> 37:07.703
don't you?Hmm.

37:11.272 --> 37:14.188
♪

37:23.066 --> 37:25.025
Well, despite how dicey
you made things

37:25.068 --> 37:26.635
for the anesthesiologist,

37:26.679 --> 37:27.854
the surgery went well.

37:27.897 --> 37:29.334
I'm gonna be okay?

37:29.377 --> 37:31.205
Yeah. Your arteries look good.

37:31.249 --> 37:32.641
But, um...

37:32.685 --> 37:34.556
before I discharge you,
I want to talk to you about

37:34.600 --> 37:36.254
your other disease.

37:38.604 --> 37:40.519
So,

37:40.562 --> 37:42.521
I took a closer look
at your labs,

37:42.564 --> 37:45.959
and your liver enzymes
are elevated.

37:46.002 --> 37:47.047
So?

37:47.090 --> 37:49.876
Is there any chance that...

37:49.919 --> 37:51.225
you don't take your medications

37:51.269 --> 37:53.271
because you can't drink alcohol
on them?

37:54.315 --> 37:56.361
[scoffs] Okay.

37:56.404 --> 37:58.711
What are you saying?
That-that I'm an alcoholic?

37:58.754 --> 38:00.408
I'm saying someone
who chooses alcohol

38:00.452 --> 38:01.975
over life-saving meds,

38:02.018 --> 38:03.368
or who ingests marijuana

38:03.411 --> 38:04.934
while they're being prepped
for surgery,

38:04.978 --> 38:07.720
or who burned so many bridges
with his ex-wife

38:07.763 --> 38:09.069
that she won't even give
him her number,

38:09.112 --> 38:10.331
might have another disease.

38:10.375 --> 38:12.899
But that's one
that can be treated, too.

38:12.942 --> 38:14.901
This is a good rehab,

38:14.944 --> 38:16.946
and they've got
nightly meetings.

38:18.165 --> 38:21.168
[scoffs] Yeah, I'm sure
they're awesome.They are,

38:21.211 --> 38:23.344
actually.

38:23.388 --> 38:25.433
Take it from a fellow alcoholic.

38:26.565 --> 38:30.917
Listen, I know how hard it is
to admit that you got a problem.

38:30.960 --> 38:34.355
And, uh,
no one here even knows this,

38:34.399 --> 38:37.097
but I've been where you are.

38:37.140 --> 38:39.839
And it cost me
someone I care about, too.

38:41.536 --> 38:43.756
But there's a solution.

38:50.719 --> 38:53.896
♪

39:01.426 --> 39:03.645
He's gonna make it.

39:03.689 --> 39:05.691
SAM: He has
a long road ahead.

39:05.734 --> 39:08.346
Yeah, well, at least
there's a road.

39:08.389 --> 39:10.913
Five years ago,
his condition would've been

39:10.957 --> 39:12.306
a death sentence.

39:12.350 --> 39:13.307
Hmm.

39:13.351 --> 39:14.656
But he has a chance,

39:14.700 --> 39:17.398
because he has you
for his doctor.

39:17.442 --> 39:18.834
And he only had you

39:18.878 --> 39:22.795
as his doctor
because we have you as a leader.

39:22.838 --> 39:25.841
You think Hamamura would've
brought that baby to Griff?

39:25.885 --> 39:27.495
I appreciate that,

39:27.539 --> 39:29.149
but I'm only
an interim solution.

39:29.192 --> 39:30.803
Oh, so, you're telling me
that we can change

39:30.846 --> 39:33.153
that baby's genetic code,

39:33.196 --> 39:35.416
but you can't change
the board's mind?

39:35.460 --> 39:38.288
I can't even talk to them.

39:38.332 --> 39:40.639
You have to be
a department head.Hmm. Right.

39:40.682 --> 39:44.207
If only you knew one
who owed you a favor.

39:44.251 --> 39:47.341
You fought
for that baby's future.

39:48.429 --> 39:50.866
Now go fight for yours.

39:54.870 --> 39:56.916
HAMAMURA:
I know it's last-minute,

39:56.959 --> 39:59.179
but Dr. Griffith was there
when I needed help.

39:59.222 --> 40:03.313
Calling this meeting was the
least I could do to thank her.

40:03.357 --> 40:06.055
I know that you don't think
the I'm right person

40:06.099 --> 40:07.709
for the position of chief.

40:07.753 --> 40:09.668
To be honest, neither did I.

40:09.711 --> 40:11.626
I thought I was gonna

40:11.670 --> 40:13.846
finish my fellowship
and move on.

40:13.889 --> 40:15.891
I had an offer
from the Cleveland Clinic.

40:15.935 --> 40:17.937
And then I thought,

40:17.980 --> 40:20.461
"I am good at this."

40:20.505 --> 40:21.941
Patients are thriving,

40:21.984 --> 40:24.334
and doctors are, too.

40:24.378 --> 40:27.468
They are happier than they were
under my father,

40:27.512 --> 40:29.296
which means they are
more effective.

40:29.339 --> 40:30.340
They are more efficient.

40:30.384 --> 40:32.168
They're more successful.

40:32.212 --> 40:34.475
There's a baby alive today
to prove it.

40:34.519 --> 40:37.783
You all asked me
to step in as chief.

40:37.826 --> 40:41.526
And now my father is awake, and
you are asking me to step aside,

40:41.569 --> 40:44.180
and I can't do that.

40:44.224 --> 40:46.269
Which is why
I'm not going anywhere.

40:46.313 --> 40:48.707
We are a better department,

40:48.750 --> 40:51.405
and we are better doctors,

40:51.449 --> 40:55.627
because I am a better chief.

41:05.767 --> 41:09.292
You know, the tyrannosaurus rex
was a merciless predator,

41:09.336 --> 41:12.252
unrivaled by any creature
of its age.

41:13.209 --> 41:14.602
I take this as a compliment.

41:14.646 --> 41:16.517
You should take it
as a warning.

41:16.561 --> 41:17.823
Oh?

41:17.866 --> 41:19.694
I spoke with the board.

41:19.738 --> 41:23.132
They share my enthusiasm
for this department's future,

41:23.176 --> 41:25.439
which means yours is
not guaranteed.

41:26.832 --> 41:28.355
They're not just gonna hand you
the reins at the end of this.

41:28.398 --> 41:30.096
They're gonna choose between us.

41:33.795 --> 41:37.277
May the best Dr. Griffith win?

41:37.320 --> 41:38.887
Is that what you want?

41:38.931 --> 41:41.107
You can be the T. rex, Dad.

41:41.150 --> 41:43.762
I'm the meteorite.

41:43.805 --> 41:44.719
And I'm coming for you.
